🔁 Common GitHub Commands Cheat Sheet

Task	Command
Clone repo	git clone <repo-url>
Check status	git status
Stage files	git add . or git add <file>
Commit	git commit -m "message"
Push changes	git push origin main
Pull updates	git pull origin main
Create new branch	git checkout -b new-branch-name
Switch branch	git checkout branch-name
Merge branches	git merge branch-name

✅ 1. Create a New Repository on GitHub
Go to GitHub.com

Click the "+" button in the top right > "New repository"

Fill in:

Repository name (e.g., my-first-repo)

Description (optional)

Choose Public or Private

DO NOT check "Initialize with a README" (important if you're starting from local)

Click "Create repository"

You’ll see a page with instructions — keep it open

💻 2. Open Your Terminal / Command Prompt
Navigate to your project folder or create a new one:


cd path/to/your/project-folder
Or create one:

mkdir my-first-repo
cd my-first-repo
⚙️ 3. Initialize a Local Git Repository

git init
This sets up Git in your folder (creates a hidden .git folder).

📁 4. Add Your Project Files
If you don’t have files yet, you can create one:

echo "# My First Project" > README.md
Then check the status:


git status
📦 5. Stage and Commit Your Files
Add all files to staging:

git add .
Commit the files:

git commit -m "Initial commit"
🔗 6. Link Your Local Repo to GitHub
Copy the GitHub repo URL (from the repo page, like https://github.com/username/my-first-repo.git) and run:


git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/your-repo-name.git
🚀 7. Push Your Local Repo to GitHub
bash

git push -u origin main
If you get an error, try using master instead of main (depends on your Git settings):

bash
Copy
Edit
git push -u origin master
✅ Done!
Now, refresh your GitHub repo page — you’ll see your files uploaded!

💡 Bonus Tips
If Git asks for your GitHub login, you can either use your GitHub username and a personal access token (PAT) instead of your password (GitHub no longer allows password auth).

To avoid entering credentials every time, you can set up SSH authentication.

